        <name>22.1.3.2 Multiplying diagonal matrices</name>
        <questiontext>&lt;p class="HELM_exercise"&gt;Exercise&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;If \[A = {@A@},\] \[B = {@B@}\] and \[C = {@C@}\] find:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol class="HELM_parts"&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;div&gt;\(AB =\) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]&lt;/div&gt;[[feedback:prt1]]
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;&lt;div&gt;\(BC =\) [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]&lt;/div&gt;
[[feedback:prt2]]
&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;</questiontext>
        <questiontextformat>1</questiontextformat>
        <generalfeedback>&lt;p&gt;Here we have the following matrices:&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span&gt;\[ \bf A = {@A@}, B = {@B@}, C = {@C@}. \]&lt;br&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;To multiply matrix \(\bf A\) by matrix \(\bf B\) we need to remember that the \((i,j)^{\textrm{th}}\) entry in the new matrix is the scalar product of the \(i^{\textrm{th}}\) row of \(\bf A\)&amp;nbsp;with the \(j^{\textrm{th}}\) column of \(\bf B\).&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;For example to obtain the element in row 1, column 2 of the new matrix&amp;nbsp;\(\bf A \bullet B\) we take row 1 of \(\bf A\), [{@A[1,1]@}, {@A[1,2]@}], and multiply it with column 2 of \(\bf B\), [{@B[1,2]@}, {@B[2,2]@}], in the usual way to produce \[ [{@A[1,1]@}\times{@B[1,2]@} +&amp;nbsp;{@A[1,2]@}\times{@B[2,2]@}] = [{@ta1[1,2]@}]. \]&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;span style="color: inherit; font-size: 10pt;"&gt;So,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\[ \bf A\bullet B =&amp;nbsp;{@A@} \bullet {@B@} = {@D1@} = {@ta1@}.\]&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;Similarly,&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;\[ \bf B\bullet C = {@B@} \bullet {@C@} = {@D2@} = {@ta2@}.\]&lt;br&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</generalfeedback>
